One of my Mom’s favorite movies and mine is The Wizard of Oz.  So, I took her and my brother to Xmas dinner @culverhotel 

Ever since The Wizard of Oz was filmed at Culver City's MGM Studios in 1939, rumors have swirled about the film's "Munchkins" reportedly staying in the Culver Hotel. 

Legend has it, the Munchkins threw wild parties at the hotel and used its underground tunnel to get to the studio. Seth Horowitz, general manager of the Culver Hotel, confirmed that all 124 Munchkins stayed at the Culver for the duration 
of filming; although he couldn't speak to their alleged shenanigans - he did note the Munchkins slept three to a bed.

We have a Hallmark ornament with Dorothy and the Scarecrow that’s been a tradition in our family - both of which mean everything to me.

Here’s wishing those whose family have passed on that you are still able to carry on traditions honoring their memory.  Those who still have family - honor, cherish and hold them tight as none of us knows what the future holds ❤️🎄🥰

Every woman in my household loved the Today show for one reason and one reason only…Barbara Walters.  It would be the first time I ever saw a woman on the news standing toe to toe with her male counterparts and was ecstatic when she later signed a multimillion deal with ABC. This network gave us The View - which is my morning staple.

Her yearly interview special airing the night before the Oscars was also a staple in my household as often times whoever she interviewed would more than likely take home an Academy Award.

She set the standard for journalists…period.  Much like @oprah, I emulated her interview skills and style even speaking about something as fluffy as entertainment or films. 

Part of her legacy will be the fact that there would be no Curvy Critic had Barbara Walters not lived.  So grateful for the simple gift of simply her. My life and career has forever been changed 💔

Moore celebrated some major milestones in 2022 including the 55th anniversary of “Hair” and the 50th anniversary of the “Melba Moore and Clifton Davis Hour.”

Melba was the first African American actress to take over a leading role from a white actress on Broadway when she replaced Diane Keaton in the role of Sheila in the 1969 company of “Hair,” 
while breaking boundaries as the first African American female entertainer to host a network variety television show alongside her then boyfriend Clifton Davis.
They were literally the first Black couple to co-host a weekly variety series on CBS in 1972. What an accomplishment and how lucky we are to have witnessed both talents grow and stretch over the decades.

So for the last few #blackhistorymonth celebrations I have highlighted those fantabulous Black people in film, tv, pioneering in science and women.  This year I’m focusing on 30 graduates from my beloved @howard1867 .  Since I’m behind a few days here goes the first of three - Taraji P. Henson.

Best known for playing strong female characters, notably Loretha (“Cookie”) Lyon in the television drama Empire (2015–20), she 
originally wanted to study electrical engineering. But when she failed precalculus, she transferred to Howard University and earned a theater arts degree. 

Her film roles started off small, but she hit it big with "Hustle & Flow," playing Shug. Howard's vocal contribution to the film's keynote song, "It's Hard Out Here for a Pimp,” helped earn the track an Academy Award for its artists composers Three 6 Mafia.

In "Benjamin Button," she ages almost 50 years on the screen as the mother of Brad Pitt's title character and her performance earned a SAG Award and Oscar nomination.

In Hidden Figures (2016) Henson was cast as Katherine Johnson, a mathematician who played a key role at NASA in the 1960s. 

Critics praised Henson for keeping the outrageous “tiger mom” Cookie from becoming a caricature, and in 2016 she won a Golden Globe for her performance. Empire’s sixth and final season, which aired in 2020, ended early because of the COVID-19 pandemic. Henson later appeared as Miss Hannigan in the TV movie Annie Live! (2021) and just recently completed filming the revival film adaptation of Alice Walker’s “The Color Purple” - where this time she’s tackling Shug Avery (a part originated by Oscar Nominee Margaret Avery)

Howard Alumni spotlight #2

Best known in his multiple Emmy nominated role as Andre 'Dre' Johnson on Black-ish, Marlin Boulet on K-Ville, and as NYPD Detective Kevin Bernard on the NBC crime drama Law & Order, Anthony Anderson had major roles in feature films such as Me, Myself & Irene (2000), Kangaroo Jack (2003), Agent Cody Banks 2: Destination London (2004), The Departed (2006), Transformers (2007), and Scream 4 (2011).

But to US, he was that crazy ATM machine thief in “Barbershop” who had audiences dying with 😂 

Since June 2016, he has served as host of the ABC version of the game show To Tell the Truth and as a guest panelist for various game shows.

What can I say about this HU Bison right here that hasn’t already been said?!

He was a bright light in our industry who gave all Black artists hope - especially those from “the Mecca.” From Jackie Robinson to James Brown to Thurgood Marshall to T’Challa - Boseman made his cinematic mark in. Very short period of time like a comet grazing over the earth.

During his two-decade career, Boseman received multiple accolades, including two Screen Actors Guild Awards, a Golden Globe Award, a Critics' Choice Movie Award, and a Primetime Emmy Award, and an Academy Award nomination.

Chadwick Boseman passed from this realm after a vigilant fight against Olin Cancer.  Ironically, he lost his battle on Jackie Robinson Day.

Another infamous HU grad - Born in Houston, Isaiah Washington’s Dad was murdered when he was 13 years old.  At 19, he joined the Air Force and after his service made his way to Howard University (where rumor has it he was an engineering major before making his way to Vera Katz and the School of Fine Arts).

At the time proving that Denzel wasn’t the only Black leading man in Hollywood.  Like Denzel, he would work with Spike Lee on “Clockers,” “Girl 6,” “Crooklyn” and “Get on the Bus” before landing  his iconic roles in such films as “Love Jones” and as Dr. Preston Burke on the hit ABC drama “Grey’s Anatomy.”

Since then, his has hopped onto the producer side with such films as “Blue Caprice,” “Not 4 Sale (a Sidney Poitier short),” “Blackbird” and “Corsicana”

HU spotlight #5
Anna Pauline “Pauli” Murray was an American civil rights activist who became a lawyer, gender equality advocate, Episcopal priest, and author. 

In 1977, she became one of the first women—and the first African-American woman—to be ordained as an Episcopal priest.

She was the only woman in her class in the law school at Howard University graduating first in her class.
She was notoriously denied the opportunity to do post-grad work at Harvard University simply due to her gender.

She would go on to earn a master's degree in law at University of California, Berkeley, and in 1965 became the first African American to receive a Doctor of Juridical Science degree from Yale Law School.

As a lawyer, she argues for civil rights and women’s rights, in addition to, being appointed by President John F. Kennedy to serve on the 1961–1963 Presidential Commission on the Status of Women.

In 1966, the late Ruth Bader Ginsburg named Murray as a coauthor of the ACLU brief in the landmark 1971 Supreme Court case Reed v. Reed, in recognition of her pioneering work on gender discrimination. 

On July 1, 1985, Pauli Murray died of pancreatic cancer. 

Her legacy lives on…
In April 2016, Yale University announced that it had selected Murray as the namesake of one of two new residential colleges (Pauli Murray College) completed in 2017. 

In January 2021, My Name Is Pauli Murray premiered at the 2021 Sundance Film Festival directed by Julie Cohen and Betsy West (who also directed the RBG Documentary)

Murray will be an honoree on an American Women quarter in 2024.

As we continue to celebrate the 50th Anniversary of Hip Hop, let me enlighten you to the genius that is Cathy Hughes. 

As TV-One’s legendary Founder and Chairwoman Hughes was named on Variety's 50 Greatest Hip-Hop Executives of All Time list.

She may not be a household name, but Hughes is a trailblazer for both female music executives and hip-hop culture. As the first female VP and general manager at WHUR in Washington, D.C., she pioneered the “Quiet Storm” format. She then founded Urban One (originally known as Radio One) in 1980, which became the largest Black-owned and -operated radio and television broadcast company in the U.S., and in 1999 was the first Black female to head a company listed on NASDAQ; by 2007, the company owned 70 stations in 22 markets. She has been listed as the second-richest Black woman in the United States — after Oprah Winfrey.

#TBT to another #hiphop legend - the overweight lover himself Heavy D, who played an influential role in shaping
rap during the late ‘80s and early ‘90s with a fusion of New Jack Swing and reggae.

Born Dwight Arrington Myers, he joined Sean “Puffy” Combs, Jermaine Dupri, Suge Knight, Dallas Austin and Russell Simmons as moguls who transformed their street credibility into boardroom positions. 

In 1997, he was appointed president and chief executive of the label that launched his career and had gone on to become a well-oiled machine of New Jack Swing — placing R&B melodies over hip-hop beats — with artists like Jodeci, Mary J. Blige and Monifah. 

He would ultimately go on to be promoted to SR. VP for Universal Music.

Like Ice-T, Queen Latifah and Ice Cube, he later focused on a successful acting career including roles in “The Cider House Rules,” “Life” and “Tower Heist.” 

On the small screen, he was featured in recent "Law & Order SVU” and “Tyler Perry’s House of Payne.”

In 2006, Heavy D would receive a NAACP Spirit Award for his starring role as a Vietnam veteran in the play “Medal of Honor Rag," and earn a Drama Desk Award nomination for his 1995 starring role in the off-Broadway play “Riff Raff.”

Unfortunately, fans would not be blessed to see where this transition would take him. Heavy D passed away after collapsing outside his Beverly Hills home in 2014 at the age of 44🥺

It’s the third day and principle of Kwanzaa UJIMA - which stands for Collective Work and Responsibility.

So, I’m taking this day to be responsible and let those of you who don’t KNOW what Kwanzaa is or why it is celebrated know what and why. 😉

Created in 1966 by Maulana Ron Karenga, Kwanzaa is an African American and Pan-African holiday that celebrates history, values, family, community and culture. The ideas and concepts of Kwanzaa are expressed in the Swahili language, one of the most widely spoken languages in Africa through seven principles.

For a great education and understanding check out The Black Candle documentary on @primevideo narrated by the late Dr. Maya Angelou and directed by Scholar/Activist @mkasante
